  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, the passage also explicitly mentions the fact that this force reproduces itself (\"sich fortpflanzende\"), which highlights the importance of reproduction for Kant's concept of an organism.",
    "Even single-cell organisms are materially autonomous: Given suitable environmental conditions, the organism will be able to keep matter organized in a way conducive to its own functioning: it establishes and maintains a membrane, a distinction between itself and the environment, it will initiate chemical processes providing it with the energy needed for its functioning, etc.",
    "The very moment it stops doing that is the moment it has ceased to be an organism; it's dead.",
    "We note that LLMs have no such material autonomy; they do not care about their continued existence.",
    "For centuries, it has gone almost without saying that material autonomy is a precondition for cognitive/moral autonomy (but not vice versa): Not all animals are rational, but all rational beings are (also) organisms."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}